TY  - JOUR
T1  - Estimation of a Longitudinal Model to Decompose the Effects of an Advertising Stimulus on Family Consumption
AU  - Winer, Russell S.
Y1  - 1980/05/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.26.5.471
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.26.5.471
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 471
EP  - 482
VL  - 26
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - A model which separates the various effects of an advertising experiment on a family's consumption behavior is estimated using consumer panel data. It is determined that there were significant transitory or short-run effects of the advertising, while permanent influences and price-advertising interactions were negligible. Implications of both the empirical results for management and the modeling approach for market researchers are discussed.
AB  - A model which separates the various effects of an advertising experiment on a family's consumption behavior is estimated using consumer panel data. It is determined that there were significant transitory or short-run effects of the advertising, while permanent influences and price-advertising interactions were negligible. Implications of both the empirical results for management and the modeling approach for market researchers are discussed.
